1
00:00:00,300 --> 00:00:05,500
The year 1985. NASA researcher Rick Briggs wrote —

2
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:11,000
Sanskrit is the world's most suitable language for computers.

3
00:00:11,400 --> 00:00:17,300
And its foundation? About 2,500 years ago,
Panini wrote 4,000 sutras

4
00:00:17,400 --> 00:00:23,400
describing the entire grammar of the language —
exactly like a program.

5
00:00:23,900 --> 00:00:31,200
See the power of Sanskrit — every word is spoken
exactly as it is written.

6
00:00:31,300 --> 00:00:38,500
Every sentence, perfectly unambiguous.
As if this language were made for computers.

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:48,000
So we thought — a language this perfect, could it not
become a programming language itself? Why not!

8
00:00:48,500 --> 00:00:56,500
That is why we built — Sanskrita!
A real programming language, entirely in Sanskrit.

9
00:00:56,600 --> 00:01:05,300
Vada. Yadi. Yaavat. Vidhi.
And Panini's karakas too.

10
00:01:05,900 --> 00:01:17,100
This is no translation — it has its own engine. Decimals always exact.
Sandhi and meter — built into the language itself.

11
00:01:17,700 --> 00:01:29,100
Our dream — Sanskrita standing proudly among the world's
finest languages. Open source — for everyone, free forever.

12
00:01:29,600 --> 00:01:34,100
And this is only the beginning. Jayatu Sanskritam!
